ther than exchange, Coffee closes his powerful case that these poems constitute far-reaching critiques of Roman society during its transition from republic to empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aNegotiationzRome. 0aReciprocity (Commerce)zRome. 0aWar in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  awar, epic writings, legends, literature, literary works, criticism, classics, classical, latin, social order, society, structures, exchange, aeneid, virgil, lucan, statius, thebaid, roman, rome, ancient, gifts, favors, payments, forms of interaction, aristocrats, aristocratic, elites, reciprocal, reciprocation, reciprocity, customs, humanity, human interactions, traditional values, commercialism, empire, negotiation, aeneas, caesar.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226111902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226111902/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles